b) Written procedures for operating and maintaining the process;

c) Training for employees involved with system operations and maintenance;

d) Written procedures for safely introducing modifications to the process;

e) Investigating the causes of releases and near misses and implementing measures to prevent recurrence; 

f) Written procedures for conducting hot work on or near the covered process;

g) Contractor management policies to ensure contract employee safety while on facility premises;

h) Audit procedures for ensuring that the programs are being implemented in accordance with the regulations; and

i) Employee involvement in program development and implementation. 



In addition, there are several engineering controls to reduce the chance of an accidental release to the environment.  Examples of these controls include:



1) Equipment monitoring systems and safety cutouts to shut off the equipment when operating parameters exceed safe operating limits.  

2) Relief valves on pressurized ammonia vessels prevent equipment rupture in the event of overpressurization.  

3) The Engine Room is equipped with ammonia detectors to warn personnel of a leak, and a ventilation system to provide continuous and emergency ventilation.  

4) Emergency stop switches for the process are in place to allow personnel to stop flow of ammonia or shut down the system in case of adverse conditions.  



Regular inspections and tests are performed to ensure these controls are in good working order.



Five Year Accident History



